rComments: I dropped Stats before and I was not expecting to do as good in his class, but he really is amazing. He makes the material interesting, lectures are super chill, open to questions and very understanding prof. He didn't make us memorize formulas as exams were open book, he cared more about our understanding and ability to interpret the material.

He kinda grew on me after a while. He wants you to understand how to interpret the data instead of just number crunching. Can go off a tangent if a particular concept comes up, but will explain things to you until you're good with it.
Would recommend taking both stats with him. Bonus is he recycle some questions.

He is one of the best stats profs every and trust me, I've dropped stats 3x before until I had him and I'm glad I stuck around. He is caring, kind, always available for extra help, really cares about his students success and will give you marks even if you get it wrong but show your work. He's definitely math focused but shows you stepbystep

Donohue is a gem. Very humorous and light lectures. You don't need to attend them, but you should because he mentions important things. There are no regular labs in the 2106 and 2116 courses with him, but they are available if you ask. He gives tutorials which are super good. Practice the sheets he gives you- similar questions are always on tests.

This class was by far the most confusing one ever. It is very math heavy. It felt like the focus was solely on computations and no application. Being able to compute a formula is one thing but when you have no idea of when/why to use each formula that creates a problem! The course outline, weekly content and textbook chapters did not match.

LOTs of work, incredibly math based, very computational, calculative, etc. We didn't use SPSS much, mostly Excel. He's a very intelligent prof and I think how advanced his understanding is really clouds his ability to teach 2nd yrs. His course is just a LOT - you have to really pay attention, review a lot, practice. Takes forever to reply to emails

Good guy. Knowledgeable in his own way. Willing to explain things if you don't understand. However, I have strong opinions in the way he structures the content for stats 1. The textbook is great though.

Professor Donohue is very thorough. He tends to ramble sometimes in his lectures, but he is clearly very passionate and experienced in statistics and this is showcased in his lectures. While the topic isn't the most exciting to most, he does his best to make the material easy to understand. He is also very easy to get ahold of via email.

Gets off track and rambles A LOT. All assignments/tests are open book which is good. Even repeats some questions from previous tests/assignments on the final. Not as hard as most stats courses. Didn't get through much material. Felt like he spent more time talking about his job than teaching. Noisy background when teaching from home.

Lectures were filled with random personal tangents that had no relevance to the course and I regretted coming to class every single time. He seemed to care more about talking about himself than teaching a course, meaning when he was finished talking about himself, he rushed through actual course content. Do not take the course with this prof.

Honestly such a sweetheart. I'm 100% sure that if I were to take the course with another prof it would have been so much worse. I'm so glad I took it with him and so grateful that he allows cheat sheets. Although I found the course super boring, I would 100% reccommend him.

Professor Donohue is such a sweetheart and wants you to do well. Always ask questions and approach him for further clarification. His exam reviews are very helpful and he even offers a few hints here and there. He allows 1 cheat sheet for midterm and 2 for the final .. you can write the entire course on the papers and he doesn't mind. Wonderful lad

Great stats 2 prof. I went in to the midterm and test having a very clear idea of what would be tested. He threw in some stats 1 material so make sure you're fresh (hint: z-scores). Assignments very easy, midterm and final VERY long but no surprises. PRACTICE before his tests to do well (speed and content). Classes end with an hour left each class.
Such a good prof who actually cares

Really, really dull lecturer. Goes off on tangents that are completely unrelated to the course. Be prepared to be tested on more "theory" than actual math. Picky grading criteria, won't even tell you about some of it in class. Ends class an hour early for homework and help, which is nice if you need it.
He's always there to help! 3 hour class ends in 2 and gave us a whole hour of working time, when we could ask him questions. Fair grader!
Absolutely brutal. Not clear, and exams are extremely long. Avoid at all costs.

Lectures with this professor primarily comprise personal anecdotes and tangents unrelated to course material. Extremely frustrating midterms as nothing is actually learned in lectures, therefore, impossible to be prepared for evaluations. Although he seems like a genuinely nice individual, as a professor, I would NOT recommend.

Unorganised and tends to go into long, unrelated tangents. We spent a month of class preparing for a presentation worth 4%. Never used the textbook, but then half the final was from it. Exams are VERY long, and don't be fooled into thinking it'll be easy because of the allowed cheat sheets. The only stats we did was correlations

Clarity: He often seems very straightforward and relatively easy to understand; other times he's too far ahead. Helpfulness: Always willing to help, but he also downplays the difficulty of the work. Easiness: Assignments are easy, and the course content itself isn't so bad. The problem is the LONG exams. If you are a slow test taker, it's over.
He was so helpful. if you as him for help and he doesn't have the time he'll make sure a TA helps you. He held refresher and question classes the weekends before exams. loved him.

Decent up to the final. He prides himself in giving unnecessarily long exams. DO the practice questions not only to be able to do them properly but to be able to do them fast. Only one person finished the final, the rest didn't. He apparently purposely does this every year and then just bell curves. I would avoid him if there's a better option.

The assignments aren't worth much and they seem so simple, but he is looking for very specific answers. The midterm and final WILL take the full 3 hours to complete. Practice questions helped. The most helpful prof ever. Went to him with my midterm and we went over it question by question and he took extra time to explain what I didn't understand

He quickly goes through material and doesn't help you understand, must do a lot of your own teaching to do well in his class. Doesn't give clear expectations on midterms or assignments. I went to laurier and took stats there and they have ressources to help such as mock midterms and help center. I wish they had something to help here.

Avoid if possible. Assignment expectations are ambiguous at best. Very friendly and personable, however he is prone to asking class to answer questions on subjects that have not been taught while expecting full participation. Exams are dreadfully long and will cover everything you've been shown (and more).

I personally find this professor to be horrible. He flies through the slides like there's no tomorrow. He's hard to understand, and laughs at students who ask questions. I asked him for help once, he told me to go ask the TA instead. I asked her, and she told me she couldn't help me. Personally, I just left class feeling angry.
Very good stats prof. Infinitely better than the alternatives. Very clear, extremely helpful. If you do the exercises in class you will do better on the exams.
Very helpful, very clear.
It is all "watching" repeating the slides in classes. You need to prepare well before class and need a lot of time studying by yourself.

The problem with this prof is that although he seems nice at first, he exudes a sense of superiority in the sense that he believes Stats is easy and cant understand why you dont get it.  He will also tell you that there are no trick questions, AFTER the work has been completed, which consequently makes the question a trick question.
